\par Abstract: Do people move to cities because of marriage market considerations? In cities
\par singles can meet more potential partners than in rural areas. Singles are
\par therefore prepared to pay a premium in terms of higher housing prices. Once
\par married, the marriage market benefits disappear while the housing premium remains.
\par We extend the model of Burdett and Coles (1997) with a distinction between efficient
\par (cities) and less efficient (non-cities) search markets. One implication of the
\par model is that singles are more likely to move from rural areas to cities while
\par married couples are more likely to make the reverse movement. A second prediction
\par of the model is that attractive singles benefit most from a dense market
\par (i.e. from being choosy). Those predictions are tested with a unique Danish dataset.
