\par Abstract: A frequent criticism of unit root tests concerns the poor
\par power and size properties that many of such tests exhibit. However, the past
\par decade or so intensive research has been conducted to alleviate these problems
\par and great advances have been made. The present paper provides a selective
\par survey of recent contributions to improve upon both size and power of unit root
\par tests and in so doing the approach of using rigorous statistical optimality criteria
\par in the development of such tests is stressed. In addition to presenting tests
\par where improved size can be achieved by modifying the standard Dickey-Fuller
\par class of tests, the paper presents theory of optimal testing and the construction
\par of power envelopes for unit root tests under different conditions allowing for
\par serial correlation, deterministic components, assumptions regarding the initial
\par condition, non-Gaussian errors, and the use of covariates.
