\par Abstract: This paper studies equilibrium effect of fiscal policy
\par disturbances within a dynamic general equilibrium model where tax
\par evasion and underground activities are explicitly incorporated.
\par There are three main results. (i) The underground sector
\par mitigates the distortionary impact of fiscal policies, while
\par lessening the drop (and the rise) of aggregate production after
\par restrictive (expansionary) tax shocks. (ii) Tax evasion
\par and underground economy can be seen as an economic mechanism that
\par rationalizes the arise of non-keynesian effects in response to fiscal
\par policy shocks. (iii) A dynamic general equilibrium with
\par tax evasion gives a rational justification for a Laffer curve.
