\par Abstract: Delineation of the relevant market forms a pivotal part of most antitrust
\par cases. The standard approach is sequential. First the product market
\par is delineated, then the geographical market is defined. Demand and
\par supply substitution in both the product dimension and the geographical
\par dimension will normally be stronger than substitution in either dimension.
\par By ignoring this one might decide first to define products narrowly and
\par then to define the geographical extent narrowly ignoring the possibility of
\par a diagonal substitution. These reflections are important in the empirical
\par delineation of product and geographical markets. Using a unique data set
\par for prices of Norwegian and Scottish salmon, we propose a methodology
\par for simultaneous market delineation and we demonstrate that compared
\par to a sequential approach conclusions will be reversed.
