\par Abstract: In this paper we investigate the effects of different fiscal policies on the firm choice
\par to produce underground. We consider a tax evading firm operating simultaneously both
\par in the regular and in the underground economy. We suggest that such a kind of firm,
\par referred to as moonlighting firm, is able to offset the specific costs usually stressed by
\par literature on underground production, such as those suggested by Loayza (1994) and
\par Anderberg et al. (2003). Investigating the effects of different fiscal policy interventions,
\par we find that taxation is a critical parameter to define the size of capital allocation in
\par the underground production. In fact, a strong and inverse relationship is found, and
\par tax reduction is the best policy to reduce the convenience to produce underground. We
\par also confirm the depressing effect on investment of taxation (see, for instance, Summers,
\par 1981), so that tax reduction has no cost in terms of investment. By contrast, the model
\par states that while enforcement is an effective tool to reduce capital allocation in the
\par underground production, it also reduce the total capital stock. Moreover, we also suggest
\par that the allowance of incentives to capital accumulation may generate, in this specific
\par typology of firm, some unexpected effects, causing, together with a positive investment
\par process, also an increase in the share of irregularity. This finding could explain, in a
\par microeconomic framework, the evidence of Italian southern regions, where high incentives
\par are combined with high irregularity ratios.
