\par Abstract: This paper estimates a reduced form multi-sector real business cycle model that 
\par allows for sector-specific and cross-sector shocks of two different types: technology 
\par shocks and non-technology shocks. Long run restrictions identify the different kinds 
\par of shocks. There are three main findings. (i) Sector-specific technology shocks 
\par explain more than 70 percent of volatility's productivity on a sector-by-sector 
\par basis; sector-specific non-technology shocks explain, on the other hand, more than 
\par 80 percent of employment volatility in each sector. This suggests that technology 
\par shocks matters for explaining productivity fluctuations. (ii) Cross-sector technology 
\par shocks have very little explanatory power on productivity and employment, while 
\par cross-sector non-technology shocks explain more than 60 percent of employment that 
\par is reallocated across sector; this suggests that the shocks' transmission mechanism 
\par operates through non-technology shocks. (iii) Looking at the aggregate economy might 
\par produce misleading results because the relatively larger sectors drive the dynamic 
\par behavior of the aggregate economy. In this respect a disaggregate analysis may shed 
\par light on the mechanisms behind the propagation of shocks across sectors and over
\par time.
