\par Abstract: The AEL (aid effectiveness literature) studies the macroeconomic effect of development aid 
\par using cross-country or panel data econo\'acmetrics. It contains about 100 papers of which 43 
\par study whether development aid increases accumulation in the recipient country. Taking all 43 
\par aid-accumulation studies together, the results show that aid has a small insignificant positive 
\par effect on investment, and a (fairly) small significant negative effect on domestic savings. The 
\par aggregate result is thus an unclear effect on accumulation, but with regional differences.
\par When only studies of Latin American or Asian economies are considered, a small positive 
\par and statistically significant investment effect is found, together with a small negative effect on 
\par domestic savings. We conclude that in Asia and Latin America, aid is a substitute to domestic
\par savings, but has a net positive impact on investment.
