\par Abstract: The AEL (aid effectiveness literature) is econo\'acmetric studies of the macroeconomic effects of 
\par development aid. It contains about 100 papers of which 68 are reduced form estimates of the
\par  effect of aid on growth in the recipient country. The raw data show that growth is 
\par unconnected to aid, but the AEL has put so much structure on the data that all results possible 
\par have emerged. The present meta study considers both the best-set of the 68 papers and the 
\par all-set of 543 regressions published. Both sets have a positive average aid-growth elasticity, 
\par but it is small and insignificant: The AEL has not established that aid works. Using meta-
\par regression analysis it is shown that about 20 factors influence the results. Much of the 
\par variation between studies is an artifact and can be attributed to publication outlet, institu\'ac
\par tional affiliation, and specification differences. However, some of the difference between
\par studies is real. In particular, the aid-growth association is stronger for Asian countries, and 
\par the aid-growth association is shown to have been weaker in the 1970s.
