\par Abstract: The AEL (aid effectiveness literature) studies the effect of development aid using econome\'ac
\par trics on macro data. It contains about 100 papers of which a third analyzes conditional 
\par models where aid effectiveness depends upon z, so that aid only works for a certain range of 
\par the variable. The key term in this family of AEL models is thus an interaction term of z times 
\par aid. The leading candidates for z are a good policy index and aid itself. In this paper, meta-
\par analysis techniques are used (i) to determine whether the AEL has established the said 
\par interaction terms, and (ii) to identify some of the determinants of the differences in results 
\par between studies. Taking all available studies in consideration, we find no support for 
\par conditionality with respect to policy, while conditionality regarding aid itself is dubious. 
\par However, the results differ depending on the authors\rquote  institutional affiliation.
